<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="67" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Latin diffuses- means spreading, perhaps in reference to open shrub-like appearance that the branches create. No discussion of the species name is given by Verrill.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="67" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">From Panama and Costa Rica to southern California, at least.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="67" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="67">
The lax, flattened branches, large polyps that produce zig-zag appearance, large (and in this case, long) anthocodial rods and the dull brick-red coloring are clear diagnostic features for this species. The species is listed as an accepted form in 
<bibRefCitation author="Cordeiro, R" journalOrPublisher="American Fisheries Society, Bethesda, Maryland" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" url="http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&amp;id=125302" year="2018 c">Cordeiro et al. (2018c)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
